Title: Identify Usage of Idioms: Literal, Idiomatic, or Ambiguous?
Description: Your task is to identify the usage of an idiom in a sentence. For each pair of idiom and sentence provided, you must select an option that best describes the meaning of the idiom within the context of the sentence. Expected time: 1 min.
Input.meaning_0: being anxious or nervous
Input.instance_0: I've been on pins and needles because I have been sitting cross-legged for too long
Input.meaning_1: continuously or interrupted
Input.instance_1: She works round the clock by sleeping for three hours and then getting up for work again
Input.idiom_2: miles to go before I sleep
Input.meaning_2: you have a lot to do before you can rest
Input.instance_2: I have miles to go before I sleep--I still have a long way to travel before I can rest
Input.meaning_3: get what one deserves
Input.instance_3: I got my just deserts when I ordered a dessert in the restaurant
Input.meaning_4: to be in a tough situation with limited options
Input.instance_4: They had their back against the wall because there was nowhere else to sit
Answer.feedback: 1. I marked the sentence with "just deserts" as ambiguous because the "deserts" in the idiom does not actually refer to "desserts" in any way, but since they are homophones the sentence when spoken aloud may make them seem as such, and thus make it "literal."2. The sentence with "on pins and needles" is technically idiomatic even though the idiom usage is wrong. Sitting that way for too long may cause you to feel a physical sensation like "pins and needles," but that is still not literally on actual pins and needles.
